        "geographicScope": {
          "type": "federal",
          "stateVariation": true
        },
        "intro": "If your parent has Medicare and limited income, Michigan's Medicare Savings Programs can pay their Medicare premiums, deductibles, and copays. Three programs exist with different income limits and coverage levels. QMB (Qualified Medicare Beneficiary) covers the most — all Medicare premiums, deductibles, and copays for someone earning up to $1,350/month. SLMB (Specified Low-Income Medicare Beneficiary) pays the $202.90 monthly Medicare Part B premium for income up to $1,585/month. QI (Qualifying Individual) also pays the Part B premium plus provides Extra Help for prescriptions, but operates on a first-come, first-served basis with annual reapplication required.\n\nBecause these programs pay Medicare costs your parent would otherwise pay out-of-pocket, they can save thousands annually. The key difference: QMB provides no retroactive coverage, SLMB can go back up to 3 months, and QI coverage starts from the calendar year of approval.",
